    "id": "quick-start",
    "title": "Quick start (3 steps)",
    "html": "<p>Want a stack of documents from your class list? Here's the whole thing in three steps. DocForge walks you through them in order along the top: <code>1 Choose template</code>, <code>2 Upload &amp; map</code>, <code>3 Generate</code>.</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Choose a template.</strong> Pick the document you want to make for each student — for example <code>Classic certificate</code>, <code>Progress report</code>, <code>Fee receipt</code>, <code>Student ID card</code>, <code>Attendance letter</code>, or <code>Enrollment confirmation</code>. Click the card to select it, then click <code>Continue</code>.</li>\n\n<li><strong>Upload your list and map the columns.</strong> Drop a CSV or Excel file onto the upload box (or click to choose one). DocForge reads your columns and shows a row for each field on the document, with a best-guess column already filled in where it can. For each field, pick the column that feeds it from the <code>— choose column —</code> menu. Fields marked with a <code>*</code> are required — you can't continue until those are mapped. A live preview on the right updates as you go, so you can check it looks right. When the required fields are mapped, click <code>Continue</code>.</li>\n\n<li><strong>Generate the batch.</strong> Check the summary, then click <code>Generate &amp; download ZIP</code>. A progress bar tracks how many are done.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>You get a ZIP of PDFs — <strong>one per row</strong> in your list. Save it, unzip it, print or email away.</p>\n\n<div class=\"tip\">No file handy? On the upload screen, click the <a href=\"/sample-class.csv\">sample class list</a> link to download a ready-made example. Open it to see how a class list should look, or use it to try a full run end to end.</div>",
