    "id": "prepare-spreadsheet",
    "title": "Preparing your spreadsheet",
    "html": "<p>DocForge builds one document for each student by reading a list you already have — your class register, a fee sheet, an exam mark sheet. The better that list is laid out, the smoother everything else goes. This page shows you how to get it ready before you upload.</p>\n\n<h3>What file types work</h3>\n<p>You can upload any of these:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>CSV</strong> — a <code>.csv</code> file</li>\n<li><strong>Excel</strong> — a <code>.xlsx</code> or <code>.xls</code> file</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The file must be <strong>5 MB or smaller</strong>. A normal class or year-group list is tiny — well under that — so you will almost never hit the limit. If you do, it usually means images or extra sheets are bloating the file; save a fresh copy with just the list in it.</p>\n<div class=\"tip\">Both Excel and Google Sheets can save a CSV. In Excel use <em>File &gt; Save As</em> and pick <strong>CSV</strong>. In Google Sheets use <em>File &gt; Download &gt; Comma-separated values (.csv)</em>. A plain CSV is the most reliable choice if you are unsure.</div>\n\n<h3>How to lay out the list</h3>\n<p>The rule is simple: <strong>one heading row at the top, then one student per row underneath.</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Put your column titles in the <strong>very first row</strong> — for example <code>Name</code>, <code>Award</code>, <code>Teacher</code>.</li>\n<li>Put <strong>one student on each row</strong> below the headings.</li>\n<li>Keep each piece of information in its own column.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Every column you include becomes something you can connect to a field on the document. You don't have to name your columns to match DocForge — on the upload step you simply tell it, for each field, which of your columns to use. So you can keep your own familiar headings.</p>\n\n<h4>A tiny example</h4>\n<p>For a certificate, a list might look like this:</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr><th>Name</th><th>Award</th><th>Teacher</th><th>Date</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Amara Okafor</td><td>Top of the Class</td><td>Ms. Bello</td><td>15 July 2026</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Liam Chen</td><td>Most Improved</td><td>Mr. Davies</td><td>15 July 2026</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Sofia Rossi</td><td>Perfect Attendance</td><td>Ms. Bello</td><td>15 July 2026</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Here the first row names the columns, and each row after it is one certificate waiting to be made. The columns can be in any order.</p>\n\n<h3>Tips for a clean list</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Keep headings short and clear</strong> — a word or two each, like <code>Class</code> or <code>Amount</code>. Avoid blank heading cells.</li>\n<li><strong>No merged cells.</strong> Merged cells confuse the reader and can shift your data out of line. Un-merge everything so every row and column is a plain grid.</li>\n<li><strong>One heading row only.</strong> Don't stack a title, a logo, or blank spacer rows above your headings — the first row must be the column names.</li>\n<li><strong>Treat dates and marks as plain text.</strong> Whatever you type in a cell is what prints on the document. So write the date exactly as you want it to appear (for example <code>15 July 2026</code>), and type marks like <code>A+</code> or <code>78%</code> just as they should read.</li>\n<li><strong>Don't leave required details blank.</strong> Each template has one or more must-have columns — a certificate, for example, needs both the recipient's name and the award. After you upload, DocForge warns you if any row is missing one.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"note\">If two students share the exact same name, DocForge still makes a document for each — it just adds a number to the duplicate filenames (for example <code>-2</code>, <code>-3</code>) so nothing gets overwritten. You don't need to fix this yourself, but adding a column like an ID or class can help you tell them apart later.</div>\n\n<h3>Not sure your file is right?</h3>\n<p>On the upload step, before you add a file, there's a <strong>sample class list</strong> you can download and open in Excel or Google Sheets. Use it as a model for how your own list should look, or just try it out to see the whole process end to end. Once your file is ready, head to <em>Upload your list &amp; map the columns</em> to bring it in.</p>",
